     <td><div align="left">
       <p class="style1"><strong class="style5">Notice Regarding Social Security Administration's Death Master File</strong><br>
      </p>
     </div></td>
   </tr>
   
   <tr>
     <td class="lower"><span class="style4">Pursuant to law passed in December 2013 (Section 203 of the Bipartisan Budget Act of 2013), access to information contained in the Social Security Administration's Death Master File (DMF) is limited for a three year period beginning on the date of an individual's death.  As of March 26, 2014, access is limited to authorized users and recipients who qualify for certification. 
     <br></span>
       <p class="style4"><br>A certification process was issued by the National Technical Information Service (NTIS) late Friday, March 21, 2014.  LexisNexis has received NTIS certification, which will enable us to continue to receive ongoing updates to the DMF. </p>
       <p class="style4">NTIS's certification program for access to the DMF requires that companies that have people/users receiving DMF information have a permissible purpose under the new law and have processes in place to protect the data provided to them.  </p></td>
    </tr>
   <tr>
     <td class="lower"><span class="style4">
    The permissible purposes for receipt of the restricted DMF data are as follows:  
     <br>
     <ul class="style6">
 <li>Legitimate fraud prevention interest, and;
</li>
 <li>Legitimate business purpose pursuant to a law, governmental rule, regulation, or fiduciary duty</li></ul></span></td>
    </tr> 
  <tr>
     <td class="lower"><span class="style4"><br>
       LexisNexis is working to minimize disruption of service to our customers.  We will notify customers of requirements for access to the restricted components of the DMF shortly.</span>
       <p class="style4">Please be aware that there will be an impact on the currentness of the deceased data you receive until you qualify for access under the NTIS program.   If you do not qualify, then the deceased-records data you receive will include DMF records on file with the Social Security Administration (SSA) up to March 21, 2014.  DMF records on file with the SSA after March 21, 2014 will remain unavailable for a period of three years from the date of the individual's death, after which time they will be made available to you. </p>
       <p class="style4"><strong>Affected Services<br>
       </strong>Searches and reports that utilize the DMF and deceased information from other alternative sources are:  </p>
       <table width="60%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="margin-left: 15px;">
         <tr>
           <td align="left" valign="top">             
           <ul class="style6">
             <li>Find a Person</li>
             <li>SmartLinx&reg;Person Report</li>
            </ul>
            </td>
           <td align="left" valign="top"><ul class="style6">
             <li>Identity Report</li>
             <li>InstantID&reg;</li>
            </ul></td>
           <td align="left" valign="top"><ul class="style6">
             <li>FraudPoint&reg;</li>
            </ul></td>
         </tr>
         </table><br>
       <p class="style4">Currently, LexisNexis has 121 Million records in its deceased database.  These records include the current DMF data, as well as state data, and other proprietary data sources.  Over 27 million of these records do not come from the DMF.  For those customers that do not meet the requirements specific to the NTIS program, LexisNexis will continue to provide value as a result of our industry-leading compilation of deceased-records information from alternative sources. </p>
       <p class="style4">LexisNexis will continue to update you as additional information becomes available. </p></td>
    </tr>    
